The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Business | GPIL gears up for commodity bourse
                                                                                                                           6                                                                                      GPIL gears up for commodity bourse
          OUR SPECIAL CORRESPONDENT                              
	Calcutta, Sept. 15: Calcutta-based Gontermann-Peipers (India) Ltd has sought the permission of the Forward Markets Commission (FMC) to set up a nationwide multi-commodity exchange.         
	We have approached the FMC for setting up a commodity exchange. We will talk to foreign partners once the approval is received, Gontermann-Peipers managing director L. K. Poddar said.         
	The exchange will mainly cater to steel and metal trading. The company, which is the largest manufacturer and exporter of cast and forged rolls, sees potential for steel and iron-based contracts on the bourses.         
	We will be the third greenfield exchange in the country if our proposal is accepted by the Forward Markets Commission , Poddar said.        
	Expansion plans        
	Owned by Pramod and Vinod Mittal of Ispat Group, Gontermann-Peipers Ltd (GPIL) is on an expansion drive. It is also growing its product portfolio with value-added castings.        
	Gontermann has entered into a memorandum of understanding with the Chhattisgarh government to set up a pelletisation plant having an annual capacity of 1.2 million tonnes.         
	Capital expenditure for the plant is Rs 300 crore, and the Mittals are awaiting clearances.        
	Besides, Gontermann has plans for a value-added project in castings at a cost of Rs 48 crore.         
	The products will cater to sectors such as mining, power, railways and defence.         
	The company has enough land bank at its existing plant at Pailan for the project, which is expected to be operational in 18 months.         
	Gontermann has also embarked on a modernisation and expansion programme at an investment of Rs 75 crore.        
	The project, which is expected to be completed by the end of this month, will increase the annual manufacturing capacity of cast and forged rolls  key components for hot-rolled and cold-rolled steel mills  to 21,000 tonnes from 15,300 tonnes.         
	BSE-listed GPIL is the only local roll maker with both vertical and horizontal spin casting technology and enjoys a 40 per cent market share. It is among the top 10 players in the world.         
	GPIL reported a turnover of Rs 140 crore for the financial year ended 2009-10.                                                                                                                                      
